      "writtenOn": "2017-08-22T19:00:45Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This is a bit dangerous, since it\u0027s effectively recursive around an unknown remote resource, and could potentially lead to stack/memory being exceeded or, more likely, an ugly stack trace.\n\nCan you reformulate this as a \"for\" loop?\n\nAlso, won\u0027t using \"s[len(s)-1].Commit\" as a starting point result in duplicate commits? I think you should use the \"Next\" cursor directly here.",
      "revId": "a3c29efd6f564c8ec7c76ae49101224611fdd769",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "041f4b04_6ae67047",
        "filename": "common/api/gitiles/gitiles.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 189,
      "author": {
        "id": 1141499
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-08-22T19:23:41Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "on a repo like Chromium/src with 500k+ commits, this will take long time and worse - lots of RAM.\nThus, `s` must be freed before tail recursion call.\nHowever, how about this algo:\n\nn :\u003d c.estimateLogLength(start, end)\nreturn reverse(c.Log(start, end~(n-max(n, LIMIT))))\n\nwhere:\n * reverse and max is what Golang2 should have :)\n * estimateLogLength does estimate through binary search with some tweaks s.t.\n     len(c.Log(start, end~n)) \u003d\u003d 0\n     len(c.Log(start, end~(n-1))) \u003e 0  [*caveat]\n\n\n* The caveat is that git history isn\u0027t necessarily linear, thus \nc.Log(stat, end~1) is not necessary 1 commit smaller than c.Log(stat, end)\nand hence both estimateLogLenght gets complex and c.Log(start, end~(n-max(n, LIMIT)) may actually return \u003eLIMIT commits :(",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 189,
        "startChar": 1,
        "endLine": 189,
        "endChar": 61
      },
